On 29 November 1947, the United Nations General Assembly recommended the adoption and implementation of the Partition Plan for Mandatory Palestine. This UN plan specified borders for the Jewish and Arab states. It set the boundaries of both states, as well as the administrative unit, the future state of Israel. The proposed borders of the Jewish state were:

Western Galilee, including Eretz Yisrael (including the Jewish communities of Bethlehem and Nazareth), including all of southern Lebanon and southern Jordan (except Eilat), except the areas of the Dead Sea and along the Jordan Valley;

Jordan Valley, including Eilat and Jericho;

Nablus and Qalqiliya in the West of Jordan Valley, east of the Dead Sea and south of Gaza;

Beit Hanina (Keshet Ha’Mitzrayim) and Kfar Aza;

Eilat and all the areas west of the Dead Sea.

